story (Lawrence Lipking); and the relation of Abrams's work to current developments in literary criticism (Jonathan Culler).Two central themes run throughout: the radically metaphorical nature of Romantic thought and the tendency of today's students to find Romanticism less rational than Abrams does. While the contributors do not always agree with one another, all are keenly aware of the contemporary challenge to humanistic values. A highlight of this book is the text of Abrams's masterly reply, delivered extemporaneously at the end of the conference. Other elements include a bibliography by Stuart A. Ende, a preface by Stephen M. Parish, and an editor's note.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAbrams, M. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBooth, Wayne C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuller, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnde, Stuart A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartman, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipking, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipking, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcfarland, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWordsworth, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172768940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501727689423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501727689/original  a